(14, 1, '2019-09-12 08:22:44', '2019-09-12 08:22:44', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have always been very interested in computers and digital equipment. My first experiences of programming with a computer go back to high school years when I learnt basic programming lessons. Luckily, I was accepted for a bachelor in computer science and from which I graduated in 2014. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I started my teaching career before the post-graduate studies. I started with elementary classes for both adults and teenagers. It later developed to more advanced courses for adults only. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By the middle of my bachelor studies, I was too indulged in human science to ignore it! That, along with my skills in English, which had significantly improved due to years of experience teaching the language, set the stage for another 2 years of academic studies; this time a master\'s degree in business administration, which for its part also paid for my interest in human science. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I was married by then, and therefore, Tehran with a vast business potential seemed a very promising place for me to settle down. I moved to Tehran in 2016 and that\'s where I still live. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have never been away from computers for long. I started my professional experience in developing websites in 2016 and it has been so much fun that I hardly feel like I\'m working. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since when I started programming, open-source technologies and free question and answer platforms have been very helpful. I have always felt the burden of having to share at least parts of what I have learnt for free with others, too. That is the fundamental reason behind this website. To share, at least parts of what I have learnt on the web, especially with fellow Iranians and those native Farsi speaking web and computer enthusiasts, who find the English-dominated media too hard to understand and/or communicate with. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As an English teacher, I also try to use the website as a medium to communicate with my students and of course, other interested learners who are looking for alternative sources to acquire more knowledge about everyday applications of the language. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Due to my news translating job, I more often than not come across facts I find very interesting to share. Besides, there are things on my mind about a variety of local and global matters which I would like to expose to further development and criticism and that\'s another thing I\'m using the website for. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'About the author', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '11-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-12 08:22:44', '2019-09-12 08:22:44', '', 11, 'http://mywebsite.test/2019/09/12/miscellaneous/11-revision-v1-14/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `pw_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(16, 1, '2019-09-19 13:55:55', '2019-09-19 13:55:55', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want to integrate \"7-zip\" into MS-Windows\' command-line interface. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"objective\"} -->\n<p class=\"objective\">This article helps you download the \"7-zip standalone console version\" and integrate it with MS-Windows command-line interface which enables you to handle compressed file types through \'CMD\' with great flexibility. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Prerequisites\">Prerequisites</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here we assume that </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"className\":\"prerequisite\"} -->\n<ol class=\"prerequisite\"><li>You know how to modify the \"PATH\" environment variable. </li><li>You have installed \"7-zip\" or any other archive manager software that supports \'.7z\' files. </li><li> You are familiar with the MS-Windows command-line interface (aka \"cmd\")  and its basic functionalities.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Procedure\">Procedure</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Get <a href=\"https://www.7-zip.org/download.html\">the latest version of the application</a>. Look for an item with the description \"7-Zip Extra: standalone console version, 7z DLL, Plugin for Far Manager\" or something similar and click on the corresponding download link. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You\'ll have downloaded a \'.7z\' file which can be extracted if you have already downloaded and installed the standard \"7-zip\" application or any other supporting archive manager software. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Extract the contents of the \'.7z\' file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can either copy the \'7za.exe\', \'7za.dll\', and \'7zxa.dll\' files into your \"MS-Windows installation directory\" or add the path to the extracted directory to your \'PATH\' environment variable. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check if you have successfully integrated \"7-zip\" into MS-Windows command-line interface by typing <code>7za</code> into a \"CMD\" window. You should see something like: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>7-Zip (a) 19.00 (x64) : Copyright (c) 1999-2018 Igor Pavlov : 2019-02-21</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>Usage: 7za &lt;command&gt;  [&lt;switches&gt;…] &lt;archive_name&gt;  [&lt;file_names&gt;…] [@listfile]</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Commands&gt;<br>   a : Add files to archive<br>   b : Benchmark<br>   d : Delete files from archive<br>   e : Extract files from archive (without using directory names)<br>   h : Calculate hash values for files<br>   i : Show information about supported formats<br>   l : List contents of archive<br>   rn : Rename files in archive<br>   t : Test integrity of archive<br>   u : Update files to archive<br>   x : eXtract files with full paths</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Switches&gt;<br>    -- : Stop switches and @listfile parsing<br>   -ai[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include archives<br>   -ax[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude archives<br>   -ao{a|s|t|u} : set Overwrite mode<br>   -an : disable archive_name field<br>   -bb[0-3] : set output log level<br>   -bd : disable progress indicator<br>   -bs{o|e|p}{0|1|2} : set output stream for output/error/progress line<br>   -bt : show execution time statistics<br>   -i[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include filenames<br>   -m{Parameters} : set compression Method<br>     -mmt[N] : set number of CPU threads<br>     -mx[N] : set compression level: -mx1 (fastest) … -mx9 (ultra)<br>   -o{Directory} : set Output directory<br>   -p{Password} : set Password<br>   -r[-|0] : Recurse subdirectories<br>   -sa{a|e|s} : set Archive name mode<br>   -scc{UTF-8|WIN|DOS} : set charset for for console input/output<br>   -scs{UTF-8|UTF-16LE|UTF-16BE|WIN|DOS|{id}} : set charset for list files<br>   -scrc[CRC32|CRC64|SHA1|SHA256|*] : set hash function for x, e, h commands<br>   -sdel : delete files after compression<br>   -seml[.] : send archive by email<br>   -sfx[{name}] : Create SFX archive<br>   -si[{name}] : read data from stdin<br>   -slp : set Large Pages mode<br>   -slt : show technical information for l (List) command<br>   -snh : store hard links as links<br>   -snl : store symbolic links as links<br>   -sni : store NT security information<br>   -sns[-] : store NTFS alternate streams<br>   -so : write data to stdout<br>   -spd : disable wildcard matching for file names<br>   -spe : eliminate duplication of root folder for extract command<br>   -spf : use fully qualified file paths<br>   -ssc[-] : set sensitive case mode<br>   -sse : stop archive creating, if it can\'t open some input file<br>   -ssw : compress shared files<br>   -stl : set archive timestamp from the most recently modified file<br>   -stm{HexMask} : set CPU thread affinity mask (hexadecimal number)<br>   -stx{Type} : exclude archive type<br>   -t{Type} : Set type of archive<br>   -u[-][p#][q#][r#][x#][y#][z#][!newArchiveName] : Update options<br>   -v{Size}[b|k|m|g] : Create volumes<br>   -w[{path}] : assign Work directory. Empty path means a temporary directory<br>   -x[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude filenames<br>   -y : assume Yes on all queries</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Summary\">Summary</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"summary\"} -->\n<p class=\"summary\">This guide helps you download the latest \"7-zip standalone console version\" and integrate it into the MS-Windows command-line interface, which enables you to manage compressed files in the command-line interface with great flexibility. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Integrate \"7-zip\" with your MS-Windows command-line interface', 'This guide helps you download the latest \"7-zip standalone console version\" and integrate it into the MS-Windows command-line interface, which enables you to manage compressed files in the command-line interface with great flexibility. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'integrate-7-zip-with-your-ms-windows-command-line-interface', '', '', '2019-09-25 12:21:47', '2019-09-25 12:21:47', '', 0, 'http://mywebsite.test/?p=16', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(17, 1, '2019-09-19 14:36:15', '2019-09-19 14:36:15', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want to collect certain files of a given directory and some of its subdirectories and put them in a single archive file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"objective\"} -->\n<p class=\"objective\">This article helps you <span class=\"obj-part\">create a \'.bat\' file</span> which archives <span class=\"obj-part\">certain file types (based on extensions or partial names)</span> of <span class=\"obj-part\">desired subdirectories (you pick which directories/paths to include/exclude)</span> inside a parent directory <span class=\"obj-part\">in a \'.zip\' file</span>, using the MS Windows command-line interface.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Prerequisites\">Prerequisites</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here, we assume that</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"className\":\"prerequisite\"} -->\n<ol class=\"prerequisite\"><li>You know how to create a blank text file in MS-Windows and convert it to a DOS batch (\".bat\") file. </li><li>You are familiar with the MS-Windows command-line interface (aka \"cmd\")  and its basic functionalities.</li><li>You are familiar with regular expressions. </li><li>You have installed the \"7-zip Extra: standalone console version\" on your version of MS-Windows.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Procedure\">Procedure</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the parent directory where your target files/folders are located (this could be the root of a partition), create a new text file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Insert the following in the text file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>FOR /F \"delims=\" %%A IN (\'DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\{directory}\\\\.*$ ^.*{file name without extension}\\..*$ ^.*{{file name}\\.{file extension}}$ ^.*{partial file name}.*$ ^.*\\.{file extension}$ {... (any similar expression separated by space)}\"\') DO 7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\{.zip file name}.zip -spf2 %%~fA</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Replace <code>{directory}</code>, <code>{file name without extension}</code>, <code>{file name}</code>, <code>{file extenstion}</code>, <code>{partial file name}</code>, and <code>{.zip file name}</code> with your desired values, without curly brackets (<code>{}</code>). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Save the file as <code>{your desired name}.bat</code> and run (double click) it.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will have a <code>{.zip file name}.zip</code> file on your desktop containing all the directories (if not empty) and files you prescribed in the code above.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Explanation\">Explanation</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"Example-in-practice\">Example in practice: </h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here\'s a sample code which collects</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>all <code>bin</code> directories recursively (with their contents),</li><li>all files with the names <code style=\"font-size: 16px;\">add to archive</code> (spaces are escaped using <code style=\"font-size: 16px;\">\\</code>) regardless of their extensions,</li><li>all <code>myfile.file</code> files,</li><li>all files/directories which contain <code>name</code> in their names or extensions,</li><li> all <code>.jpg</code> files</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>inside our target directory, and puts them into the <code>archive.zip</code> file on our desktop:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\">FOR /F \"delims=\" %%A IN (\'DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"\') DO 7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip -spf2 %%~fA</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"breaking-it-up\">Breaking it up:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the heart of the code there is a <code>for</code> command: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\">FOR /F \"options\" %%variable IN (set) DO command [command-parameters] </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>with</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>file set (<code>/F</code>) parameter and its <code>\"options\"</code> denoted as <code>/F \"delims=\"</code> </li><li><code>%%variable</code> denoted as <code>%%A</code>,  </li><li><code>(set)</code> denoted as  <code>(\'DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"\')</code>,  </li><li><code>command [command-parameters]</code> denoted as <code>7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip -spf2 %%~fA</code></li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As described <a href=\"https://ss64.com/nt/for.html\">here</a>, <code>FOR</code> with <code>/F</code> takes every line of <code>(set)</code> based on rules prescribed in (\"options\"), puts it in <code>%variable</code>, and executes the <code>command [command-parameters]</code>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By using the <code>/F</code> parameter, we have instructed <code>FOR</code> that it is going to iterate over contents of a file set.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By setting <code>\"delimiter=\"</code> as the options for <code>/F</code> (leaving the value empty), we have instructed <code>FOR</code> not to treat anything as a delimiter (breaking point) in the string, except for new lines.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now let\'s see what our <code>(set)</code> does: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>(\'dir /s /b ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"\') </code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Moving inside, the first bracket (<code>(</code>) is just the opening delimiter of the set scope and the single quote (<code>\'</code>) declares that we want <code>FOR</code> to iterate over lines of a string. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thus, <code>FOR</code>, in each iteration of its loop is passing a line of the output produced by <code>DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"</code> and putting it in <code>%%A</code>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As per the <a href=\"https://ss64.com/nt/dir.html\">manual page</a>, <code>DIR /S /B</code> lists the contents of a directory, recurses into its subdirectories, and omits the extra information (i.e. no heading, file sizes, or summary). The additional <code>^</code> means the output produced by <code>DIR</code> consists of more than one line, and that they all together should be piped (<code>|</code>) into the next command, which in our example is <code>findstr</code>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><code>findstr</code> searches inside the output of our <code>DIR</code> and returns the lines that match any of the regular expression patterns (separated by spaces) inside double quotes (<code>\"\"</code>). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So far, we have a list of our files we want to archive that is iterated over, one line at a time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, to add the files to the <code>archives.zip</code> file on our desktop:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>DO 7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip -spf2 %%~fA </code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want the zip (<code>-tzip</code>) archive (<code>%userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip)</code> to be updated (the<code>u</code> command), i.e. keep the files already inside the archive and only replace them if the given file (<code>%%~fA</code>) is newer than the one in the archive. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We are using <code>%%~fA</code> (full path to file) instead of simply using <code>%%A</code> because we want the archive file to save the full directory structure of the files which are being archived. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Summary\">Summary</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"summary\"} -->\n<p class=\"summary\">Using the MS-Windows command-line interface, this guide helps us create a \'.bat\' file which, by the help of the \"7-zip standalone console version\", creates a \'.zip\' file from files and directories we specify. The code to create the \'.bat\' file is fully explained and can be customized based on users\' needs. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"References\">References</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I would like to thank the people who wrote these, as if it wasn\'t for their help, I would not have learnt what is written above. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"className\":\"references\"} -->\n<ul class=\"references\"><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8055371/how-do-i-run-two-commands-in-one-line-in-windows-cmd\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8055371/how-do-i-run-two-commands-in-one-line-in-windows-cmd</a></li><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19878136/how-can-i-use-a-batch-file-to-write-to-a-text-file/19879594\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19878136/how-can-i-use-a-batch-file-to-write-to-a-text-file/19879594</a></li><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2376801/recursive-directory-listing-in-dos\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2376801/recursive-directory-listing-in-dos</a></li><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29976780/forfile-command-to-delete-all-except-a-directory\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29976780/forfile-command-to-delete-all-except-a-directory</a></li><li><a href=\"https://superuser.com/questions/653860/list-files-recursively-showing-only-full-path-and-file-size-from-windows-command\">https://superuser.com/questions/653860/list-files-recursively-showing-only-full-path-and-file-size-from-windows-command</a></li><li><a href=\"https://superuser.com/questions/383641/excluding-files-of-particular-extension-using-dir-command-on-windows-command-lin\">https://superuser.com/questions/383641/excluding-files-of-particular-extension-using-dir-command-on-windows-command-lin</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Archive certain directories/files using MS Windows command-line interface', 'Collect certain files/directories of a given directory and put them in a single archive file. ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '5-autosave-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 14:36:15', '2019-09-19 14:36:15', '', 5, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/5-autosave-v1-20190919-17/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(18, 1, '2019-09-19 13:55:55', '2019-09-19 13:55:55', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want to install a version of the well-known \"7-zip\" file compression tool that integrates into MS-Windows\' command-line interface and offers great flexibilities. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here we assume that </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>You know how to modify the <code>PATH</code> environment variable. </li><li>You have installed \"7-zip\" or any other archive manager software that supports <code>.7z</code> files. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Get <a href=\"https://www.7-zip.org/download.html\">the latest version of the application</a>. Look for an item with the description \"7-Zip Extra: standalone console version, 7z DLL, Plugin for Far Manager\" or something similar and click on the corresponding download link. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You\'ll have downloaded a <code>.7z</code> file which can be extracted if you have already downloaded and installed the normal \"7-zip\" application or any other supporting archive manager software. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Extract the files inside the <code>.7z</code> file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can either copy the <code>7za.exe</code>, <code>7za.dll</code>, and <code>7zxa.dll</code> into your MS-Windows directory or add the path to the extracted directory to your PATH environment variable. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check if you have successfully integrated \"7-zip\" into MS-Windows command-line interface by typing <code>7za</code> into a <code>CMD </code>window. You should see something like: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>7-Zip (a) 19.00 (x64) : Copyright (c) 1999-2018 Igor Pavlov : 2019-02-21</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>Usage: 7za &lt;command>  [&lt;switches>…] &lt;archive_name>  [&lt;file_names>…] [@listfile]</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Commands><br>   a : Add files to archive<br>   b : Benchmark<br>   d : Delete files from archive<br>   e : Extract files from archive (without using directory names)<br>   h : Calculate hash values for files<br>   i : Show information about supported formats<br>   l : List contents of archive<br>   rn : Rename files in archive<br>   t : Test integrity of archive<br>   u : Update files to archive<br>   x : eXtract files with full paths</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Switches><br>    -- : Stop switches and @listfile parsing<br>   -ai[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include archives<br>   -ax[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude archives<br>   -ao{a|s|t|u} : set Overwrite mode<br>   -an : disable archive_name field<br>   -bb[0-3] : set output log level<br>   -bd : disable progress indicator<br>   -bs{o|e|p}{0|1|2} : set output stream for output/error/progress line<br>   -bt : show execution time statistics<br>   -i[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include filenames<br>   -m{Parameters} : set compression Method<br>     -mmt[N] : set number of CPU threads<br>     -mx[N] : set compression level: -mx1 (fastest) … -mx9 (ultra)<br>   -o{Directory} : set Output directory<br>   -p{Password} : set Password<br>   -r[-|0] : Recurse subdirectories<br>   -sa{a|e|s} : set Archive name mode<br>   -scc{UTF-8|WIN|DOS} : set charset for for console input/output<br>   -scs{UTF-8|UTF-16LE|UTF-16BE|WIN|DOS|{id}} : set charset for list files<br>   -scrc[CRC32|CRC64|SHA1|SHA256|*] : set hash function for x, e, h commands<br>   -sdel : delete files after compression<br>   -seml[.] : send archive by email<br>   -sfx[{name}] : Create SFX archive<br>   -si[{name}] : read data from stdin<br>   -slp : set Large Pages mode<br>   -slt : show technical information for l (List) command<br>   -snh : store hard links as links<br>   -snl : store symbolic links as links<br>   -sni : store NT security information<br>   -sns[-] : store NTFS alternate streams<br>   -so : write data to stdout<br>   -spd : disable wildcard matching for file names<br>   -spe : eliminate duplication of root folder for extract command<br>   -spf : use fully qualified file paths<br>   -ssc[-] : set sensitive case mode<br>   -sse : stop archive creating, if it can\'t open some input file<br>   -ssw : compress shared files<br>   -stl : set archive timestamp from the most recently modified file<br>   -stm{HexMask} : set CPU thread affinity mask (hexadecimal number)<br>   -stx{Type} : exclude archive type<br>   -t{Type} : Set type of archive<br>   -u[-][p#][q#][r#][x#][y#][z#][!newArchiveName] : Update options<br>   -v{Size}[b|k|m|g] : Create volumes<br>   -w[{path}] : assign Work directory. Empty path means a temporary directory<br>   -x[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude filenames<br>   -y : assume Yes on all queries</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Install \"7-zip Extra: standalone console version\" on your MS-Windows system', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 13:55:55', '2019-09-19 13:55:55', '', 16, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/16-revision-v1-20190919-18/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(19, 1, '2019-09-19 14:03:53', '2019-09-19 14:03:53', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want to install a version of the well-known \"7-zip\" file compression tool that integrates into MS-Windows\' command-line interface and offers great flexibilities. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here we assume that </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>You know how to modify the \"PATH\" environment variable. </li><li>You have installed \"7-zip\" or any other archive manager software that supports \'.7z\' files. </li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Get <a href=\"https://www.7-zip.org/download.html\">the latest version of the application</a>. Look for an item with the description \"7-Zip Extra: standalone console version, 7z DLL, Plugin for Far Manager\" or something similar and click on the corresponding download link. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You\'ll have downloaded a \'.7z\' file which can be extracted if you have already downloaded and installed the standard \"7-zip\" application or any other supporting archive manager software. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Extract the contents of the \'.7z\' file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can either copy the \'7za.exe\', \'7za.dll\', and \'7zxa.dll\' files into your \"MS-Windows installation directory\" or add the path to the extracted directory to your \'PATH\' environment variable. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check if you have successfully integrated \"7-zip\" into MS-Windows command-line interface by typing <code>7za</code> into a \"CMD\" window. You should see something like: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>7-Zip (a) 19.00 (x64) : Copyright (c) 1999-2018 Igor Pavlov : 2019-02-21</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>Usage: 7za &lt;command>  [&lt;switches>…] &lt;archive_name>  [&lt;file_names>…] [@listfile]</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Commands><br>   a : Add files to archive<br>   b : Benchmark<br>   d : Delete files from archive<br>   e : Extract files from archive (without using directory names)<br>   h : Calculate hash values for files<br>   i : Show information about supported formats<br>   l : List contents of archive<br>   rn : Rename files in archive<br>   t : Test integrity of archive<br>   u : Update files to archive<br>   x : eXtract files with full paths</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Switches><br>    -- : Stop switches and @listfile parsing<br>   -ai[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include archives<br>   -ax[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude archives<br>   -ao{a|s|t|u} : set Overwrite mode<br>   -an : disable archive_name field<br>   -bb[0-3] : set output log level<br>   -bd : disable progress indicator<br>   -bs{o|e|p}{0|1|2} : set output stream for output/error/progress line<br>   -bt : show execution time statistics<br>   -i[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include filenames<br>   -m{Parameters} : set compression Method<br>     -mmt[N] : set number of CPU threads<br>     -mx[N] : set compression level: -mx1 (fastest) … -mx9 (ultra)<br>   -o{Directory} : set Output directory<br>   -p{Password} : set Password<br>   -r[-|0] : Recurse subdirectories<br>   -sa{a|e|s} : set Archive name mode<br>   -scc{UTF-8|WIN|DOS} : set charset for for console input/output<br>   -scs{UTF-8|UTF-16LE|UTF-16BE|WIN|DOS|{id}} : set charset for list files<br>   -scrc[CRC32|CRC64|SHA1|SHA256|*] : set hash function for x, e, h commands<br>   -sdel : delete files after compression<br>   -seml[.] : send archive by email<br>   -sfx[{name}] : Create SFX archive<br>   -si[{name}] : read data from stdin<br>   -slp : set Large Pages mode<br>   -slt : show technical information for l (List) command<br>   -snh : store hard links as links<br>   -snl : store symbolic links as links<br>   -sni : store NT security information<br>   -sns[-] : store NTFS alternate streams<br>   -so : write data to stdout<br>   -spd : disable wildcard matching for file names<br>   -spe : eliminate duplication of root folder for extract command<br>   -spf : use fully qualified file paths<br>   -ssc[-] : set sensitive case mode<br>   -sse : stop archive creating, if it can\'t open some input file<br>   -ssw : compress shared files<br>   -stl : set archive timestamp from the most recently modified file<br>   -stm{HexMask} : set CPU thread affinity mask (hexadecimal number)<br>   -stx{Type} : exclude archive type<br>   -t{Type} : Set type of archive<br>   -u[-][p#][q#][r#][x#][y#][z#][!newArchiveName] : Update options<br>   -v{Size}[b|k|m|g] : Create volumes<br>   -w[{path}] : assign Work directory. Empty path means a temporary directory<br>   -x[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude filenames<br>   -y : assume Yes on all queries</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Integrate \"7-zip\" with your MS-Windows command-line interface', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 14:03:53', '2019-09-19 14:03:53', '', 16, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/16-revision-v1-20190919-19/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(20, 1, '2019-09-19 14:05:46', '2019-09-19 14:05:46', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want to install a version of the well-known \"7-zip\" file compression tool that integrates into MS-Windows\' command-line interface and offers great flexibilities. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here we assume that </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>You know how to modify the \"PATH\" environment variable. </li><li>You have installed \"7-zip\" or any other archive manager software that supports \'.7z\' files. </li><li> You are familiar with the MS-Windows command-line interface (aka \"cmd\")  and its basic functionalities.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Get <a href=\"https://www.7-zip.org/download.html\">the latest version of the application</a>. Look for an item with the description \"7-Zip Extra: standalone console version, 7z DLL, Plugin for Far Manager\" or something similar and click on the corresponding download link. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You\'ll have downloaded a \'.7z\' file which can be extracted if you have already downloaded and installed the standard \"7-zip\" application or any other supporting archive manager software. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Extract the contents of the \'.7z\' file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can either copy the \'7za.exe\', \'7za.dll\', and \'7zxa.dll\' files into your \"MS-Windows installation directory\" or add the path to the extracted directory to your \'PATH\' environment variable. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check if you have successfully integrated \"7-zip\" into MS-Windows command-line interface by typing <code>7za</code> into a \"CMD\" window. You should see something like: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>7-Zip (a) 19.00 (x64) : Copyright (c) 1999-2018 Igor Pavlov : 2019-02-21</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>Usage: 7za &lt;command>  [&lt;switches>…] &lt;archive_name>  [&lt;file_names>…] [@listfile]</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Commands><br>   a : Add files to archive<br>   b : Benchmark<br>   d : Delete files from archive<br>   e : Extract files from archive (without using directory names)<br>   h : Calculate hash values for files<br>   i : Show information about supported formats<br>   l : List contents of archive<br>   rn : Rename files in archive<br>   t : Test integrity of archive<br>   u : Update files to archive<br>   x : eXtract files with full paths</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Switches><br>    -- : Stop switches and @listfile parsing<br>   -ai[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include archives<br>   -ax[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude archives<br>   -ao{a|s|t|u} : set Overwrite mode<br>   -an : disable archive_name field<br>   -bb[0-3] : set output log level<br>   -bd : disable progress indicator<br>   -bs{o|e|p}{0|1|2} : set output stream for output/error/progress line<br>   -bt : show execution time statistics<br>   -i[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include filenames<br>   -m{Parameters} : set compression Method<br>     -mmt[N] : set number of CPU threads<br>     -mx[N] : set compression level: -mx1 (fastest) … -mx9 (ultra)<br>   -o{Directory} : set Output directory<br>   -p{Password} : set Password<br>   -r[-|0] : Recurse subdirectories<br>   -sa{a|e|s} : set Archive name mode<br>   -scc{UTF-8|WIN|DOS} : set charset for for console input/output<br>   -scs{UTF-8|UTF-16LE|UTF-16BE|WIN|DOS|{id}} : set charset for list files<br>   -scrc[CRC32|CRC64|SHA1|SHA256|*] : set hash function for x, e, h commands<br>   -sdel : delete files after compression<br>   -seml[.] : send archive by email<br>   -sfx[{name}] : Create SFX archive<br>   -si[{name}] : read data from stdin<br>   -slp : set Large Pages mode<br>   -slt : show technical information for l (List) command<br>   -snh : store hard links as links<br>   -snl : store symbolic links as links<br>   -sni : store NT security information<br>   -sns[-] : store NTFS alternate streams<br>   -so : write data to stdout<br>   -spd : disable wildcard matching for file names<br>   -spe : eliminate duplication of root folder for extract command<br>   -spf : use fully qualified file paths<br>   -ssc[-] : set sensitive case mode<br>   -sse : stop archive creating, if it can\'t open some input file<br>   -ssw : compress shared files<br>   -stl : set archive timestamp from the most recently modified file<br>   -stm{HexMask} : set CPU thread affinity mask (hexadecimal number)<br>   -stx{Type} : exclude archive type<br>   -t{Type} : Set type of archive<br>   -u[-][p#][q#][r#][x#][y#][z#][!newArchiveName] : Update options<br>   -v{Size}[b|k|m|g] : Create volumes<br>   -w[{path}] : assign Work directory. Empty path means a temporary directory<br>   -x[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude filenames<br>   -y : assume Yes on all queries</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Integrate \"7-zip\" with your MS-Windows command-line interface', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 14:05:46', '2019-09-19 14:05:46', '', 16, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/16-revision-v1-20190919-20/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(22, 1, '2019-09-19 14:37:36', '2019-09-19 14:37:36', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want to collect certain files of a given directory and some of its subdirectories and put them in a single archive file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"objective\"} -->\n<p class=\"objective\">This article helps you <span class=\"obj-part\">create a \'.bat\' file</span> which archives <span class=\"obj-part\">certain file types (based on extensions or partial names)</span> of <span class=\"obj-part\">desired subdirectories (you pick which directories/paths to include/exclude)</span> inside a parent directory <span class=\"obj-part\">in a \'.zip\' file</span>, using the MS Windows command-line interface.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Prerequisites\">Prerequisites</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here, we assume that</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"className\":\"prerequisite\"} -->\n<ol class=\"prerequisite\"><li>You know how to create a blank text file in MS-Windows and convert it to a DOS batch (\".bat\") file. </li><li>You are familiar with the MS-Windows command-line interface (aka \"cmd\")  and its basic functionalities.</li><li>You are familiar with regular expressions. </li><li>You have installed the \"7-zip Extra: standalone console version\" on your version of MS-Windows.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Procedure\">Procedure</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the parent directory where your target files/folders are located (this could be the root of a partition), create a new text file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Insert the following in the text file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>FOR /F \"delims=\" %%A IN (\'DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\{directory}\\\\.*$ ^.*{file name without extension}\\..*$ ^.*{{file name}\\.{file extension}}$ ^.*{partial file name}.*$ ^.*\\.{file extension}$ {... (any similar expression separated by space)}\"\') DO 7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\{.zip file name}.zip -spf2 %%~fA</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Replace <code>{directory}</code>, <code>{file name without extension}</code>, <code>{file name}</code>, <code>{file extenstion}</code>, <code>{partial file name}</code>, and <code>{.zip file name}</code> with your desired values, without curly brackets (<code>{}</code>). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Save the file as <code>{your desired name}.bat</code> and run (double click) it.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will have a <code>{.zip file name}.zip</code> file on your desktop containing all the directories (if not empty) and files you prescribed in the code above.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Explanation\">Explanation</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"Example-in-practice\">Example in practice: </h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here\'s a sample code which collects</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>all <code>bin</code> directories recursively (with their contents),</li><li>all files with the names <code style=\"font-size: 16px;\">add to archive</code> (spaces are escaped using <code style=\"font-size: 16px;\">\\</code>) regardless of their extensions,</li><li>all <code>myfile.file</code> files,</li><li>all files/directories which contain <code>name</code> in their names or extensions,</li><li> all <code>.jpg</code> files</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>inside our target directory, and puts them into the <code>archive.zip</code> file on our desktop:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\">FOR /F \"delims=\" %%A IN (\'DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"\') DO 7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip -spf2 %%~fA</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"breaking-it-up\">Breaking it up:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the heart of the code there is a <code>for</code> command: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\">FOR /F \"options\" %%variable IN (set) DO command [command-parameters] </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>with</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>file set (<code>/F</code>) parameter and its <code>\"options\"</code> denoted as <code>/F \"delims=\"</code> </li><li><code>%%variable</code> denoted as <code>%%A</code>,  </li><li><code>(set)</code> denoted as  <code>(\'DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"\')</code>,  </li><li><code>command [command-parameters]</code> denoted as <code>7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip -spf2 %%~fA</code></li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As described <a href=\"https://ss64.com/nt/for.html\">here</a>, <code>FOR</code> with <code>/F</code> takes every line of <code>(set)</code> based on rules prescribed in (\"options\"), puts it in <code>%variable</code>, and executes the <code>command [command-parameters]</code>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By using the <code>/F</code> parameter, we have instructed <code>FOR</code> that it is going to iterate over contents of a file set.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By setting <code>\"delimiter=\"</code> as the options for <code>/F</code> (leaving the value empty), we have instructed <code>FOR</code> not to treat anything as a delimiter (breaking point) in the string, except for new lines.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now let\'s see what our <code>(set)</code> does: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>(\'dir /s /b ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"\') </code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Moving inside, the first bracket (<code>(</code>) is just the opening delimiter of the set scope and the single quote (<code>\'</code>) declares that we want <code>FOR</code> to iterate over lines of a string. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thus, <code>FOR</code>, in each iteration of its loop is passing a line of the output produced by <code>DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"</code> and putting it in <code>%%A</code>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As per the <a href=\"https://ss64.com/nt/dir.html\">manual page</a>, <code>DIR /S /B</code> lists the contents of a directory, recurses into its subdirectories, and omits the extra information (i.e. no heading, file sizes, or summary). The additional <code>^</code> means the output produced by <code>DIR</code> consists of more than one line, and that they all together should be piped (<code>|</code>) into the next command, which in our example is <code>findstr</code>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><code>findstr</code> searches inside the output of our <code>DIR</code> and returns the lines that match any of the regular expression patterns (separated by spaces) inside double quotes (<code>\"\"</code>). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So far, we have a list of our files we want to archive that is iterated over, one line at a time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, to add the files to the <code>archives.zip</code> file on our desktop:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>DO 7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip -spf2 %%~fA </code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want the zip (<code>-tzip</code>) archive (<code>%userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip)</code> to be updated (the<code>u</code> command), i.e. keep the files already inside the archive and only replace them if the given file (<code>%%~fA</code>) is newer than the one in the archive. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We are using <code>%%~fA</code> (full path to file) instead of simply using <code>%%A</code> because we want the archive file to save the full directory structure of the files which are being archived. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Summary\">Summary</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"summary\"} -->\n<p class=\"summary\">Using the MS-Windows command-line interface, this guide helps us create a \'.bat\' file which, by the help of the \"7-zip standalone console version\", creates a \'.zip\' file from files and directories we specify. The code to create the \'.bat\' file is fully explained and can be customized based on users\' needs. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"References\">References</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I would like to thank the people who wrote these, as if it wasn\'t for their help, I would not have learnt what is written above. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"className\":\"references\"} -->\n<ul class=\"references\"><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8055371/how-do-i-run-two-commands-in-one-line-in-windows-cmd\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8055371/how-do-i-run-two-commands-in-one-line-in-windows-cmd</a></li><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19878136/how-can-i-use-a-batch-file-to-write-to-a-text-file/19879594\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19878136/how-can-i-use-a-batch-file-to-write-to-a-text-file/19879594</a></li><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2376801/recursive-directory-listing-in-dos\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2376801/recursive-directory-listing-in-dos</a></li><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29976780/forfile-command-to-delete-all-except-a-directory\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29976780/forfile-command-to-delete-all-except-a-directory</a></li><li><a href=\"https://superuser.com/questions/653860/list-files-recursively-showing-only-full-path-and-file-size-from-windows-command\">https://superuser.com/questions/653860/list-files-recursively-showing-only-full-path-and-file-size-from-windows-command</a></li><li><a href=\"https://superuser.com/questions/383641/excluding-files-of-particular-extension-using-dir-command-on-windows-command-lin\">https://superuser.com/questions/383641/excluding-files-of-particular-extension-using-dir-command-on-windows-command-lin</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Archive certain directories/files using MS Windows command-line interface', 'Collect certain files/directories of a given directory and put them in a single archive file. ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 14:37:36', '2019-09-19 14:37:36', '', 5, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/5-revision-v1-20190919-22/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `pw_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(23, 1, '2019-09-19 14:42:34', '2019-09-19 14:42:34', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want to integrate \"7-zip\" into MS-Windows\' command-line interface. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"objective\"} -->\n<p class=\"objective\">This article helps you download the \"7-zip standalone console version\" and integrate it with MS-Windows command-line interface which enables you to handle compressed file types through \'CMD\' with great flexibility. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Prerequisites\">Prerequisites</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here we assume that </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"className\":\"prerequisite\"} -->\n<ol class=\"prerequisite\"><li>You know how to modify the \"PATH\" environment variable. </li><li>You have installed \"7-zip\" or any other archive manager software that supports \'.7z\' files. </li><li> You are familiar with the MS-Windows command-line interface (aka \"cmd\")  and its basic functionalities.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Procedure\">Procedure</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Get <a href=\"https://www.7-zip.org/download.html\">the latest version of the application</a>. Look for an item with the description \"7-Zip Extra: standalone console version, 7z DLL, Plugin for Far Manager\" or something similar and click on the corresponding download link. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You\'ll have downloaded a \'.7z\' file which can be extracted if you have already downloaded and installed the standard \"7-zip\" application or any other supporting archive manager software. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Extract the contents of the \'.7z\' file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can either copy the \'7za.exe\', \'7za.dll\', and \'7zxa.dll\' files into your \"MS-Windows installation directory\" or add the path to the extracted directory to your \'PATH\' environment variable. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check if you have successfully integrated \"7-zip\" into MS-Windows command-line interface by typing <code>7za</code> into a \"CMD\" window. You should see something like: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>7-Zip (a) 19.00 (x64) : Copyright (c) 1999-2018 Igor Pavlov : 2019-02-21</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>Usage: 7za &lt;command>  [&lt;switches>…] &lt;archive_name>  [&lt;file_names>…] [@listfile]</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Commands><br>   a : Add files to archive<br>   b : Benchmark<br>   d : Delete files from archive<br>   e : Extract files from archive (without using directory names)<br>   h : Calculate hash values for files<br>   i : Show information about supported formats<br>   l : List contents of archive<br>   rn : Rename files in archive<br>   t : Test integrity of archive<br>   u : Update files to archive<br>   x : eXtract files with full paths</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Switches><br>    -- : Stop switches and @listfile parsing<br>   -ai[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include archives<br>   -ax[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude archives<br>   -ao{a|s|t|u} : set Overwrite mode<br>   -an : disable archive_name field<br>   -bb[0-3] : set output log level<br>   -bd : disable progress indicator<br>   -bs{o|e|p}{0|1|2} : set output stream for output/error/progress line<br>   -bt : show execution time statistics<br>   -i[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include filenames<br>   -m{Parameters} : set compression Method<br>     -mmt[N] : set number of CPU threads<br>     -mx[N] : set compression level: -mx1 (fastest) … -mx9 (ultra)<br>   -o{Directory} : set Output directory<br>   -p{Password} : set Password<br>   -r[-|0] : Recurse subdirectories<br>   -sa{a|e|s} : set Archive name mode<br>   -scc{UTF-8|WIN|DOS} : set charset for for console input/output<br>   -scs{UTF-8|UTF-16LE|UTF-16BE|WIN|DOS|{id}} : set charset for list files<br>   -scrc[CRC32|CRC64|SHA1|SHA256|*] : set hash function for x, e, h commands<br>   -sdel : delete files after compression<br>   -seml[.] : send archive by email<br>   -sfx[{name}] : Create SFX archive<br>   -si[{name}] : read data from stdin<br>   -slp : set Large Pages mode<br>   -slt : show technical information for l (List) command<br>   -snh : store hard links as links<br>   -snl : store symbolic links as links<br>   -sni : store NT security information<br>   -sns[-] : store NTFS alternate streams<br>   -so : write data to stdout<br>   -spd : disable wildcard matching for file names<br>   -spe : eliminate duplication of root folder for extract command<br>   -spf : use fully qualified file paths<br>   -ssc[-] : set sensitive case mode<br>   -sse : stop archive creating, if it can\'t open some input file<br>   -ssw : compress shared files<br>   -stl : set archive timestamp from the most recently modified file<br>   -stm{HexMask} : set CPU thread affinity mask (hexadecimal number)<br>   -stx{Type} : exclude archive type<br>   -t{Type} : Set type of archive<br>   -u[-][p#][q#][r#][x#][y#][z#][!newArchiveName] : Update options<br>   -v{Size}[b|k|m|g] : Create volumes<br>   -w[{path}] : assign Work directory. Empty path means a temporary directory<br>   -x[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude filenames<br>   -y : assume Yes on all queries</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Summary\">Summary</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"summary\"} -->\n<p class=\"summary\">This guide helps you download the latest \"7-zip standalone console version\" and integrate it into the MS-Windows command-line interface, which enables you to manage compressed files in the command-line interface with great flexibility. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Integrate \"7-zip\" with your MS-Windows command-line interface', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 14:42:34', '2019-09-19 14:42:34', '', 16, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/16-revision-v1-20190919-23/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(24, 1, '2019-09-19 15:30:16', '2019-09-19 15:30:16', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In February 2019, India (as the New Delhi government claimed) responded to a brutal terrorist attack in Pulwama by bombarding what they claimed to be a terrorists\' base in Balakot, Pakistan. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pakistan was reportedly quick to scramble American F-16 fighter jets to repel the Indian Air Force raid on its soil. Only to realize later that they might have violated some end-user restrictions on using the jets. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/us-seeks-information-on-potential-misuse-of-f-16-by-pakistan/articleshow/68229586.cms\">A report</a> from the Indian Economic Times has only partially elaborated on how the Pakistani Army has trapped itself into an agreement with the US over the purchase of the military equipment which it can\'t use even as means of self-defence.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The report quotes a top US State Department official as saying \"There is a two-man rule, so to speak, for access to this equipment and restricted areas, and F-16 flights outside of Pakistan or participation in exercises and operations with third nations must be approved in advance by the United States government\". </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meaning that take for example the incident described above, the Pakistani Army had to actually ask for US consent before using F-16s to repel Indian bombers! In other words, by the time the Pakistani Army\'s F-16s would have the permission to take off, if by any luck they did secure the permission, the Indian strikers would have been telling stories of their heroic anti-terrorist operation to their beloved children in bed. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Seriously? Are US-provided fighters so good that can track down perpetrators of an attack to the purchaser\'s unchallenged sovereign territory hours after the attack, while they\'re in bed? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Why relying on arms from foreign superpowers endangers a nation\'s sovereignty', 'Relying on a foreign superpower for military equipment not only endangers sovereignty, it will also have little effects on improving a nation\'s self-defence. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'why-relying-on-arms-from-foreign-superpowers-endangers-a-nations-sovereignty', '', '', '2019-09-19 15:41:10', '2019-09-19 15:41:10', '', 0, 'http://mywebsite.test/?p=24', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(25, 1, '2019-09-19 15:30:16', '2019-09-19 15:30:16', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In February 2019, India (as the New Delhi government claimed) responded to a brutal terrorist attack in Pulwama by bombarding what they claimed to be a terrorists\' base in Balakot, Pakistan. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pakistan was reportedly quick to scramble American F-16 fighter jets to repel the Indian Air Force raid on its soil. Only to realize later that they might have violated some end-user restrictions on using the jets. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/us-seeks-information-on-potential-misuse-of-f-16-by-pakistan/articleshow/68229586.cms\">A report</a> from the Indian Economic Times has only partially elaborated on how the Pakistani Army has trapped itself into an agreement with the US over the purchase of the military equipment which it can\'t use even as means of self-defence.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The report quotes a top US State Department official as saying \"There is a two-man rule, so to speak, for access to this equipment and restricted areas, and F-16 flights outside of Pakistan or participation in exercises and operations with third nations must be approved in advance by the United States government\". </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meaning that take for example the incident described above, the Pakistani Army had to actually ask for US consent before using F-16s to repel Indian bombers! In other words, by the time the Pakistani Army\'s F-16s would have the permission to take off, if by any luck they did secure the permission, the Indian strikers would have been telling stories of their heroic anti-terrorist operation to their beloved children in bed. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Seriously? Are US-provided fighters so good that can track down perpetrators of an attack to the purchaser\'s unchallenged sovereign territory hours after the attack, while they\'re in bed? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Why relying on warfare from imperialist powers endangers a nation\'s sovereignty', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '24-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 15:30:16', '2019-09-19 15:30:16', '', 24, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/24-revision-v1-20190919-25/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(26, 1, '2019-09-19 15:36:36', '2019-09-19 15:36:36', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In February 2019, India (as the New Delhi government claimed) responded to a brutal terrorist attack in Pulwama by bombarding what they claimed to be a terrorists\' base in Balakot, Pakistan. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pakistan was reportedly quick to scramble American F-16 fighter jets to repel the Indian Air Force raid on its soil. Only to realize later that they might have violated some end-user restrictions on using the jets. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/us-seeks-information-on-potential-misuse-of-f-16-by-pakistan/articleshow/68229586.cms\">A report</a> from the Indian Economic Times has only partially elaborated on how the Pakistani Army has trapped itself into an agreement with the US over the purchase of the military equipment which it can\'t use even as means of self-defence.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The report quotes a top US State Department official as saying \"There is a two-man rule, so to speak, for access to this equipment and restricted areas, and F-16 flights outside of Pakistan or participation in exercises and operations with third nations must be approved in advance by the United States government\". </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meaning that take for example the incident described above, the Pakistani Army had to actually ask for US consent before using F-16s to repel Indian bombers! In other words, by the time the Pakistani Army\'s F-16s would have the permission to take off, if by any luck they did secure the permission, the Indian strikers would have been telling stories of their heroic anti-terrorist operation to their beloved children in bed. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Seriously? Are US-provided fighters so good that can track down perpetrators of an attack to the purchaser\'s unchallenged sovereign territory hours after the attack, while they\'re in bed? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Why relying on warfare from imperialist powers endangers a nation\'s sovereignty', 'Relying on a foreign super-power for military equipment not only endangers sovereignty, it will also have little effects on improving a nation\'s self-defence. ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '24-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 15:36:36', '2019-09-19 15:36:36', '', 24, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/24-revision-v1-20190919-26/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(27, 1, '2019-09-19 15:37:27', '2019-09-19 15:37:27', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want to collect certain files of a given directory and some of its subdirectories and put them in a single archive file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"objective\"} -->\n<p class=\"objective\">This article helps you <span class=\"obj-part\">create a \'.bat\' file</span> which archives <span class=\"obj-part\">certain file types (based on extensions or partial names)</span> of <span class=\"obj-part\">desired subdirectories (you pick which directories/paths to include/exclude)</span> inside a parent directory <span class=\"obj-part\">in a \'.zip\' file</span>, using the MS Windows command-line interface.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Prerequisites\">Prerequisites</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here, we assume that</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"className\":\"prerequisite\"} -->\n<ol class=\"prerequisite\"><li>You know how to create a blank text file in MS-Windows and convert it to a DOS batch (\".bat\") file. </li><li>You are familiar with the MS-Windows command-line interface (aka \"cmd\")  and its basic functionalities.</li><li>You are familiar with regular expressions. </li><li>You have installed the \"7-zip Extra: standalone console version\" on your version of MS-Windows.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Procedure\">Procedure</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the parent directory where your target files/folders are located (this could be the root of a partition), create a new text file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Insert the following in the text file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>FOR /F \"delims=\" %%A IN (\'DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\{directory}\\\\.*$ ^.*{file name without extension}\\..*$ ^.*{{file name}\\.{file extension}}$ ^.*{partial file name}.*$ ^.*\\.{file extension}$ {... (any similar expression separated by space)}\"\') DO 7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\{.zip file name}.zip -spf2 %%~fA</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Replace <code>{directory}</code>, <code>{file name without extension}</code>, <code>{file name}</code>, <code>{file extenstion}</code>, <code>{partial file name}</code>, and <code>{.zip file name}</code> with your desired values, without curly brackets (<code>{}</code>). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Save the file as <code>{your desired name}.bat</code> and run (double click) it.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will have a <code>{.zip file name}.zip</code> file on your desktop containing all the directories (if not empty) and files you prescribed in the code above.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Explanation\">Explanation</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"Example-in-practice\">Example in practice: </h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here\'s a sample code which collects</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>all <code>bin</code> directories recursively (with their contents),</li><li>all files with the names <code style=\"font-size: 16px;\">add to archive</code> (spaces are escaped using <code style=\"font-size: 16px;\">\\</code>) regardless of their extensions,</li><li>all <code>myfile.file</code> files,</li><li>all files/directories which contain <code>name</code> in their names or extensions,</li><li> all <code>.jpg</code> files</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>inside our target directory, and puts them into the <code>archive.zip</code> file on our desktop:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\">FOR /F \"delims=\" %%A IN (\'DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"\') DO 7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip -spf2 %%~fA</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"breaking-it-up\">Breaking it up:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the heart of the code there is a <code>for</code> command: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\">FOR /F \"options\" %%variable IN (set) DO command [command-parameters] </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>with</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>file set (<code>/F</code>) parameter and its <code>\"options\"</code> denoted as <code>/F \"delims=\"</code> </li><li><code>%%variable</code> denoted as <code>%%A</code>,  </li><li><code>(set)</code> denoted as  <code>(\'DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"\')</code>,  </li><li><code>command [command-parameters]</code> denoted as <code>7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip -spf2 %%~fA</code></li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As described <a href=\"https://ss64.com/nt/for.html\">here</a>, <code>FOR</code> with <code>/F</code> takes every line of <code>(set)</code> based on rules prescribed in (\"options\"), puts it in <code>%variable</code>, and executes the <code>command [command-parameters]</code>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By using the <code>/F</code> parameter, we have instructed <code>FOR</code> that it is going to iterate over contents of a file set.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By setting <code>\"delimiter=\"</code> as the options for <code>/F</code> (leaving the value empty), we have instructed <code>FOR</code> not to treat anything as a delimiter (breaking point) in the string, except for new lines.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now let\'s see what our <code>(set)</code> does: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>(\'dir /s /b ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"\') </code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Moving inside, the first bracket (<code>(</code>) is just the opening delimiter of the set scope and the single quote (<code>\'</code>) declares that we want <code>FOR</code> to iterate over lines of a string. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thus, <code>FOR</code>, in each iteration of its loop is passing a line of the output produced by <code>DIR /S /B ^| findstr \"^.*\\\\bin\\\\.*$ ^.*add\\ to\\ archive\\..*$ ^.*myfile\\.file$ ^.*name.*$ ^.*\\.{jpg}$\"</code> and putting it in <code>%%A</code>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As per the <a href=\"https://ss64.com/nt/dir.html\">manual page</a>, <code>DIR /S /B</code> lists the contents of a directory, recurses into its subdirectories, and omits the extra information (i.e. no heading, file sizes, or summary). The additional <code>^</code> means the output produced by <code>DIR</code> consists of more than one line, and that they all together should be piped (<code>|</code>) into the next command, which in our example is <code>findstr</code>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><code>findstr</code> searches inside the output of our <code>DIR</code> and returns the lines that match any of the regular expression patterns (separated by spaces) inside double quotes (<code>\"\"</code>). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So far, we have a list of our files we want to archive that is iterated over, one line at a time. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, to add the files to the <code>archives.zip</code> file on our desktop:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>DO 7za u -tzip %userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip -spf2 %%~fA </code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want the zip (<code>-tzip</code>) archive (<code>%userprofile%\\Desktop\\arhcive.zip)</code> to be updated (the<code>u</code> command), i.e. keep the files already inside the archive and only replace them if the given file (<code>%%~fA</code>) is newer than the one in the archive. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We are using <code>%%~fA</code> (full path to file) instead of simply using <code>%%A</code> because we want the archive file to save the full directory structure of the files which are being archived. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Summary\">Summary</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"summary\"} -->\n<p class=\"summary\">Using the MS-Windows command-line interface, this guide helps us create a \'.bat\' file which, by the help of the \"7-zip standalone console version\", creates a \'.zip\' file from files and directories we specify. The code to create the \'.bat\' file is fully explained and can be customized based on users\' needs. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"References\">References</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I would like to thank the people who wrote these, as if it wasn\'t for their help, I would not have learnt what is written above. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"className\":\"references\"} -->\n<ul class=\"references\"><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8055371/how-do-i-run-two-commands-in-one-line-in-windows-cmd\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8055371/how-do-i-run-two-commands-in-one-line-in-windows-cmd</a></li><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19878136/how-can-i-use-a-batch-file-to-write-to-a-text-file/19879594\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19878136/how-can-i-use-a-batch-file-to-write-to-a-text-file/19879594</a></li><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2376801/recursive-directory-listing-in-dos\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2376801/recursive-directory-listing-in-dos</a></li><li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29976780/forfile-command-to-delete-all-except-a-directory\">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29976780/forfile-command-to-delete-all-except-a-directory</a></li><li><a href=\"https://superuser.com/questions/653860/list-files-recursively-showing-only-full-path-and-file-size-from-windows-command\">https://superuser.com/questions/653860/list-files-recursively-showing-only-full-path-and-file-size-from-windows-command</a></li><li><a href=\"https://superuser.com/questions/383641/excluding-files-of-particular-extension-using-dir-command-on-windows-command-lin\">https://superuser.com/questions/383641/excluding-files-of-particular-extension-using-dir-command-on-windows-command-lin</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Archive certain directories/files using MS Windows command-line interface', 'Using the MS-Windows command-line interface, this guide helps us create a \'.bat\' file which, by the help of the \"7-zip standalone console version\", creates a \'.zip\' file from files and directories we specify. The code to create the \'.bat\' file is fully explained and can be customized based on users\' needs. ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 15:37:27', '2019-09-19 15:37:27', '', 5, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/5-revision-v1-20190919-27/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(28, 1, '2019-09-19 15:38:43', '2019-09-19 15:38:43', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In February 2019, India (as the New Delhi government claimed) responded to a brutal terrorist attack in Pulwama by bombarding what they claimed to be a terrorists\' base in Balakot, Pakistan. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pakistan was reportedly quick to scramble American F-16 fighter jets to repel the Indian Air Force raid on its soil. Only to realize later that they might have violated some end-user restrictions on using the jets. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/us-seeks-information-on-potential-misuse-of-f-16-by-pakistan/articleshow/68229586.cms\">A report</a> from the Indian Economic Times has only partially elaborated on how the Pakistani Army has trapped itself into an agreement with the US over the purchase of the military equipment which it can\'t use even as means of self-defence.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The report quotes a top US State Department official as saying \"There is a two-man rule, so to speak, for access to this equipment and restricted areas, and F-16 flights outside of Pakistan or participation in exercises and operations with third nations must be approved in advance by the United States government\". </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meaning that take for example the incident described above, the Pakistani Army had to actually ask for US consent before using F-16s to repel Indian bombers! In other words, by the time the Pakistani Army\'s F-16s would have the permission to take off, if by any luck they did secure the permission, the Indian strikers would have been telling stories of their heroic anti-terrorist operation to their beloved children in bed. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Seriously? Are US-provided fighters so good that can track down perpetrators of an attack to the purchaser\'s unchallenged sovereign territory hours after the attack, while they\'re in bed? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Why relying on warfare from foreign superpowers endangers a nation\'s sovereignty', 'Relying on a foreign superpower for military equipment not only endangers sovereignty, it will also have little effects on improving a nation\'s self-defence. ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '24-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 15:38:43', '2019-09-19 15:38:43', '', 24, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/24-revision-v1-20190919-28/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(29, 1, '2019-09-19 15:41:10', '2019-09-19 15:41:10', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In February 2019, India (as the New Delhi government claimed) responded to a brutal terrorist attack in Pulwama by bombarding what they claimed to be a terrorists\' base in Balakot, Pakistan. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pakistan was reportedly quick to scramble American F-16 fighter jets to repel the Indian Air Force raid on its soil. Only to realize later that they might have violated some end-user restrictions on using the jets. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/us-seeks-information-on-potential-misuse-of-f-16-by-pakistan/articleshow/68229586.cms\">A report</a> from the Indian Economic Times has only partially elaborated on how the Pakistani Army has trapped itself into an agreement with the US over the purchase of the military equipment which it can\'t use even as means of self-defence.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The report quotes a top US State Department official as saying \"There is a two-man rule, so to speak, for access to this equipment and restricted areas, and F-16 flights outside of Pakistan or participation in exercises and operations with third nations must be approved in advance by the United States government\". </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meaning that take for example the incident described above, the Pakistani Army had to actually ask for US consent before using F-16s to repel Indian bombers! In other words, by the time the Pakistani Army\'s F-16s would have the permission to take off, if by any luck they did secure the permission, the Indian strikers would have been telling stories of their heroic anti-terrorist operation to their beloved children in bed. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Seriously? Are US-provided fighters so good that can track down perpetrators of an attack to the purchaser\'s unchallenged sovereign territory hours after the attack, while they\'re in bed? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Why relying on arms from foreign superpowers endangers a nation\'s sovereignty', 'Relying on a foreign superpower for military equipment not only endangers sovereignty, it will also have little effects on improving a nation\'s self-defence. ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '24-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 15:41:10', '2019-09-19 15:41:10', '', 24, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/24-revision-v1-20190919-29/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(30, 1, '2019-09-19 15:41:48', '2019-09-19 15:41:48', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We want to integrate \"7-zip\" into MS-Windows\' command-line interface. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"objective\"} -->\n<p class=\"objective\">This article helps you download the \"7-zip standalone console version\" and integrate it with MS-Windows command-line interface which enables you to handle compressed file types through \'CMD\' with great flexibility. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Prerequisites\">Prerequisites</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here we assume that </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"className\":\"prerequisite\"} -->\n<ol class=\"prerequisite\"><li>You know how to modify the \"PATH\" environment variable. </li><li>You have installed \"7-zip\" or any other archive manager software that supports \'.7z\' files. </li><li> You are familiar with the MS-Windows command-line interface (aka \"cmd\")  and its basic functionalities.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Procedure\">Procedure</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Get <a href=\"https://www.7-zip.org/download.html\">the latest version of the application</a>. Look for an item with the description \"7-Zip Extra: standalone console version, 7z DLL, Plugin for Far Manager\" or something similar and click on the corresponding download link. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You\'ll have downloaded a \'.7z\' file which can be extracted if you have already downloaded and installed the standard \"7-zip\" application or any other supporting archive manager software. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Extract the contents of the \'.7z\' file. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can either copy the \'7za.exe\', \'7za.dll\', and \'7zxa.dll\' files into your \"MS-Windows installation directory\" or add the path to the extracted directory to your \'PATH\' environment variable. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check if you have successfully integrated \"7-zip\" into MS-Windows command-line interface by typing <code>7za</code> into a \"CMD\" window. You should see something like: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>7-Zip (a) 19.00 (x64) : Copyright (c) 1999-2018 Igor Pavlov : 2019-02-21</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>Usage: 7za &lt;command&gt;  [&lt;switches&gt;…] &lt;archive_name&gt;  [&lt;file_names&gt;…] [@listfile]</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Commands&gt;<br>   a : Add files to archive<br>   b : Benchmark<br>   d : Delete files from archive<br>   e : Extract files from archive (without using directory names)<br>   h : Calculate hash values for files<br>   i : Show information about supported formats<br>   l : List contents of archive<br>   rn : Rename files in archive<br>   t : Test integrity of archive<br>   u : Update files to archive<br>   x : eXtract files with full paths</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"code\"} -->\n<p class=\"code\"><code>&lt;Switches&gt;<br>    -- : Stop switches and @listfile parsing<br>   -ai[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include archives<br>   -ax[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude archives<br>   -ao{a|s|t|u} : set Overwrite mode<br>   -an : disable archive_name field<br>   -bb[0-3] : set output log level<br>   -bd : disable progress indicator<br>   -bs{o|e|p}{0|1|2} : set output stream for output/error/progress line<br>   -bt : show execution time statistics<br>   -i[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : Include filenames<br>   -m{Parameters} : set compression Method<br>     -mmt[N] : set number of CPU threads<br>     -mx[N] : set compression level: -mx1 (fastest) … -mx9 (ultra)<br>   -o{Directory} : set Output directory<br>   -p{Password} : set Password<br>   -r[-|0] : Recurse subdirectories<br>   -sa{a|e|s} : set Archive name mode<br>   -scc{UTF-8|WIN|DOS} : set charset for for console input/output<br>   -scs{UTF-8|UTF-16LE|UTF-16BE|WIN|DOS|{id}} : set charset for list files<br>   -scrc[CRC32|CRC64|SHA1|SHA256|*] : set hash function for x, e, h commands<br>   -sdel : delete files after compression<br>   -seml[.] : send archive by email<br>   -sfx[{name}] : Create SFX archive<br>   -si[{name}] : read data from stdin<br>   -slp : set Large Pages mode<br>   -slt : show technical information for l (List) command<br>   -snh : store hard links as links<br>   -snl : store symbolic links as links<br>   -sni : store NT security information<br>   -sns[-] : store NTFS alternate streams<br>   -so : write data to stdout<br>   -spd : disable wildcard matching for file names<br>   -spe : eliminate duplication of root folder for extract command<br>   -spf : use fully qualified file paths<br>   -ssc[-] : set sensitive case mode<br>   -sse : stop archive creating, if it can\'t open some input file<br>   -ssw : compress shared files<br>   -stl : set archive timestamp from the most recently modified file<br>   -stm{HexMask} : set CPU thread affinity mask (hexadecimal number)<br>   -stx{Type} : exclude archive type<br>   -t{Type} : Set type of archive<br>   -u[-][p#][q#][r#][x#][y#][z#][!newArchiveName] : Update options<br>   -v{Size}[b|k|m|g] : Create volumes<br>   -w[{path}] : assign Work directory. Empty path means a temporary directory<br>   -x[r[-|0]]{@listfile|!wildcard} : eXclude filenames<br>   -y : assume Yes on all queries</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"Summary\">Summary</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"summary\"} -->\n<p class=\"summary\">This guide helps you download the latest \"7-zip standalone console version\" and integrate it into the MS-Windows command-line interface, which enables you to manage compressed files in the command-line interface with great flexibility. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Integrate \"7-zip\" with your MS-Windows command-line interface', 'This guide helps you download the latest \"7-zip standalone console version\" and integrate it into the MS-Windows command-line interface, which enables you to manage compressed files in the command-line interface with great flexibility. ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-09-19 15:41:48', '2019-09-19 15:41:48', '', 16, 'http://mywebsite.test/miscellaneous/16-revision-v1-20190919-30/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(31, 1, '2019-09-29 11:41:23', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 'Auto Draft', '', 'auto-draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2019-09-29 11:41:23', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://mywebsite.test/?p=31', 0, 'post', '', 0);

